[1]
Date: Thu 27 May 2004 2004
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Fort Wayne.com, Associated Press Report, Thu 27 May 2004 [edited]
<http://www.fortwayne.com/mld/newssentinel/8776916.htm>

Arizona (West): 1st human Case of West Nile Virus Infection in 2004
-------------------------------------------------
Arizona reported this year's 1st human cases of the mosquito-borne
West Nile virus, health officials said. On Wed 26 May 2004 New Mexico
reported its 1st human case. At a news conference Thu 27 May 2004,
Dr. Jonathan Weisbuch, director of the Maricopa County Department of
Public Health, said an adult from the county developed symptoms 8 May
2004 and was admitted to a hospital. Weisbuch said that person has
now fully recovered.
In all, 8 residents from Maricopa County, which includes Phoenix,
contracted the virus in 2003, but only one was infected within the
county, Weisbuch said. That case -- a person who became ill in
September 2003 and has now recovered -- was confirmed by the CDC as
West Nile virus infected earlier this month.
Arizona's mosquito season usually runs from August through September
after the monsoon rains, and "this is much earlier than we expected,"
Weisbuch said. "It's going to be a longer season. We could see
several hundred cases," he said.
Dr. Amy Bode, a medical epidemiologist for the Division of
Vector-Borne Infectious Diseases at the CDC laboratory in Fort
Collins, Colo., warned against predictions. "The 2nd year is not
necessarily (the worst) but it can be," she said. "The states should
try to be ready and take precautions."
West Nile, which first hit the United States in 1999 in New York, has
killed more than 560 people in the United States in the past 5 years.
Last year was the first for West Nile to appear in areas west of the
Continental Divide. Colorado led the nation last year with 2947 of
9862 human cases reported to the federal Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention. The disease resulted in 61 deaths in that state.
