Virginia: First Equine Case of West Nile Virus Infection in 2004
---------------------------------------------------
A 6-year-old thoroughbred mare in Culpeper County was euthanized
after contracting West Nile virus (WNV), the 1st case of the disease
in a Virginia horse this year, the state Department of Agriculture
and Consumer Services said on Fri 28 May 2004. Symptoms first
appeared on 1 May 2004, earlier than any of the previously reported
cases of West Nile in Virginia. The earliest previous case was on 15
Jul 2003.
"Even though it is very unusual to see a positive case this early in
the season, it is not too late to vaccinate your horse for WNV," said
Joe Garvin, head of the agriculture department's laboratory services
office.
West Nile vaccine for horses requires 2 doses administered 3-6 weeks
apart. The vaccine takes 4-6 weeks from the 2nd dose to be effective.
