Pndiana: West Nile Virus-infected Mosquitoes Found Earlier than Previously
--------------------------------------------------
The 1st pool of mosquitoes in Indiana infected with the West Nile
virus has been found earlier than in previous years, health officials
said on Fri 29 May 2004. The infected mosquitoes were found in traps
on the north side of Indianapolis, a location where the virus also
was detected last year, the Marion County Health Department said.
"The recent warm conditions combined with the rain we have had during
the last couple of weeks has increased our mosquito counts," said Jim
Erwin, the department's mosquito control biologist.
The virus was first detected among animals in Indiana during 2001,
and the state recorded 293 confirmed human cases of West Nile virus
infection and 11 deaths in 2002. But with several heavy storms last
summer flushing away mosquito eggs in septic ponds, roadside catch
basins and other breeding sites, only 47 cases and 4 deaths were
reported in the state.
